@end card
@end row

## Writing your own
@divider

@row
@card .primary
## Where they live
@divider

Put project directives in `directives/**/*.js` in your site.

Marque reloads them on build and during `marque serve`, so you do not need to patch the parser core to add your own components.
@end card

@card
## What a directive can define
@divider

- `type`: `block` or `inline`
- `render(...)`: returns HTML
- `validate(...)`: optional diagnostics
- `style`: optional CSS chunk injected into generated CSS
@end card
@end row

@card
```js
module.exports = ({ defineDirective }) => {
  defineDirective('product-card', {
    type: 'block',
    render: ({ mods, name, children, ctx }) => {
      const variant = ctx.escapeAttr(mods[0] || 'default');
      const title = ctx.escapeAttr(name || '');
      return `<product-card variant="${variant}" title="${title}">${children}</product-card>`;
    },
  });
};
```
@end card

@callout .ok
Most directives are small. If all you need is "wrap these children and style them", that is already enough for a useful custom directive.
@end callout

## Notes worth knowing
@divider

@row
@card
- `@container` is structural and does not emit its own wrapper element.
- `@step` numbering works best inside container flow because that is where the counter is managed.
- `@row` expects block directive children like `@card` or `@column`.
@end card

@card
- Buttons and badges are lightweight authoring syntax, not directive registry entries.
- Hyphenated names like `product-card` are supported.
- The starter directives are examples, not sacred. Replace them whenever your project needs something different.
@end card
@end row
